You’re circling around something that many mathematicians and computer scientists have been slowly moving toward for the last ~70 years.

Equations were the first language of relationships, but they are actually a very limited representation of relational structure.

Let’s unpack that.

⸻

1. Why equations are primitive

An equation has a very strict form.

It links two expressions with equality.

Example:

y = mx + b

This says:
	•	one relationship
	•	between two sides
	•	at one layer

But real systems rarely behave that simply.

Real systems are usually:
	•	many-to-many relationships
	•	nested relationships
	•	relationships between relationships
	•	dynamic transformations

An equation is basically a two-node statement.

Reality is usually a graph.

⸻

2. The hidden graph behind equations

Most equations secretly represent a network of dependencies.

Take a simple physics expression:

F = ma

F = ma

Behind this are relationships between:
	•	force
	•	mass
	•	acceleration
	•	position
	•	time

Which actually forms a causal network.

The equation is just a compressed slice of that network.

⸻

3. Why modern math is shifting toward networks

Many fields have already moved away from equation-centric thinking.

Examples:

Graph theory

Relationships are explicitly represented as nodes and edges.

Used in:
	•	internet topology
	•	biology networks
	•	social systems
	•	knowledge graphs

Category theory

Focuses on transformations between structures rather than the structures themselves.

This is almost exactly what you described:

mapping transformations between domains.

Dynamical systems

Focus on state spaces and flows, not just equations.

Machine learning

Uses neural graphs and tensors, not simple equations.

⸻

4. Networks capture relationships better

Consider a system like:
	•	language
	•	markets
	•	ecosystems
	•	cognition

Trying to describe these with equations alone is extremely awkward.

But representing them as networks of interactions works naturally.

Example structure:

Idea A → Idea B
Idea A → Idea C
Idea B → Idea D
Idea C → Idea D

This captures multi-path causality, something equations struggle with.

⸻

5. Why tensors are the next step

A tensor is basically a multi-dimensional relationship container.

Scalars → single value
Vectors → relationships along one axis
Matrices → relationships between two sets
Tensors → relationships across many dimensions

For example:

A color can encode three variables.

Red component
Green component
Blue component

One color = a 3-dimensional state vector.

This matches your idea of color encoding multi-variable information.

Modern AI models are basically giant tensor machines.

⸻

6. The future language of mathematics

Instead of writing:

equations

Future math often looks like:

graphs
operators
tensor fields
transformations

The objects are not numbers.

They are structures.

Examples already exist:
	•	network science
	•	category theory
	•	topological data analysis
	•	geometric deep learning

These treat relationships as first-class objects.

⸻

7. Metaphors as relational translation

Your observation about metaphors is very close to something in mathematics called functors.

A functor maps structure from one domain to another while preserving relationships.

Metaphor does something similar.

Example:

“Electric current flows like water.”

Mapping:

Electricity	Fluid
voltage	pressure
current	flow
resistance	pipe width

The key is finding the invariant relational pattern.

Exactly what you described as the symmetrical middle point.

⸻

